---
/**
 * GitLab CI Validator — the primary SEO surface for the GitLab CI/CD tool.
 * Paste a `.gitlab-ci.yml` and get YAML errors PLUS the structural and
 * pipeline-misconfiguration mistakes GitLab itself would reject: a job with no
 * script, a `stage` that is not in `stages:`, `needs`/`extends` pointing at jobs
 * that do not exist, an invalid `when:`, legacy `only/except`, and bad
 * `image`/`services` shapes. 100% client-side — no server, no signup.
 *
 * Mirrors the GitHub Actions Validator page structure (hero with scrimmed
 * MeshGradient, playground island, why/checks docs, dark next-step band,
 * FAQ + JSON-LD, cross-links, footer note). The interactive island
 * (GitlabCiValidatorPlayground) self-mounts; JSON-LD (SoftwareApplication +
 * FAQPage) is assembled here and handed to Shell.
 */
import Shell from '../components/Shell.astro';
import GitlabCiValidatorPlayground from '../components/GitlabCiValidatorPlayground.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Badge from '../components/Badge.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import ToolHero from '../components/ToolHero.astro';
import ToolGapVisual from '../components/ToolGapVisual.astro';
import ToolPipeline from '../components/ToolPipeline.astro';
import FaqList from '../components/FaqList.astro';
import ToolCrossLinks from '../components/ToolCrossLinks.astro';
import { site, navLinks } from '../data/site';
import { getTool } from '../data/tools';
import { softwareAppLd, faqPageLd } from '../lib/jsonld';

const tool = getTool('gitlab-ci-validator');

const pagePath = '/gitlab-ci-validator/';
const pageUrl = `${site.url}${pagePath}`;

// ── External references (the "why it exists" gap + canonical docs) ───────────
const glDocsKeywords =
  'https://docs.gitlab.com/ci/yaml/';
const glDocsStages =
  'https://docs.gitlab.com/ci/yaml/#stages';
const glDocsRules =
  'https://docs.gitlab.com/ci/yaml/#rules';
const glDocsLint =
  'https://docs.gitlab.com/ci/pipeline_editor/';

// ── FAQ content — single source for both the rendered section and FAQPage LD ─
const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How do I validate a .gitlab-ci.yml file?',
    a: 'Paste the pipeline YAML into a browser-based GitLab CI validator to catch errors before you commit — no install and no push needed. This tool runs the full check set (YAML structure plus pipeline misconfigurations) entirely in your browser, so you get instant feedback on syntax errors, undefined stages, jobs without scripts, broken needs/extends, and invalid when values before the config ever reaches a GitLab runner. Paste your .gitlab-ci.yml and validate online to get a clear pass or fail with the line and reason for each problem.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I lint GitLab CI without a project?',
    a: 'Yes. GitLab’s built-in CI Lint requires a project and a sign-in, but this validator does not. You can validate a .gitlab-ci.yml without a project, an account, or a login — just paste the YAML and the GitLab CI linter runs 100% in your browser. Nothing is uploaded to a server, so you can safely check internal or proprietary pipelines, including ones with private runner tags and secret variable references.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Why does GitLab say "this GitLab CI configuration is invalid"?',
    a: 'That message means GitLab rejected your pipeline before running it — almost always because of a structural mistake rather than bad YAML. The usual causes are a job with no script / run / trigger / extends, a job whose stage is not in your stages list, needs or extends pointing at a job that does not exist, an invalid when value, or a rules block that is not a list. To fix "this GitLab CI configuration is invalid", paste your .gitlab-ci.yml here: the validator runs the same high-signal checks and tells you exactly which job and key broke, with the fix.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I check my .gitlab-ci.yml for errors before pushing?',
    a: 'Run a GitLab CI YAML lint in the browser before you commit. Paste the config into this validator and it checks both the YAML and the pipeline structure — undefined stages, jobs without scripts, broken needs/extends, invalid when — so you can validate a GitLab CI pipeline before push. A clean result here is strong pre-push confidence; for absolute certainty, confirm with GitLab’s own CI Lint, which also resolves includes and project variables.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is there a free online GitLab CI validator with no login?',
    a: 'Yes. This is a free GitLab CI YAML validator with no signup, no install, and no login. It runs entirely client-side in your browser, so there is no account to create and nothing to upload. Paste your .gitlab-ci.yml and validate online instantly — the tool is free to use as often as you like.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What does the GitLab CI Lint tool actually check?',
    a: 'Two things at once. First, it parses your .gitlab-ci.yml and reports YAML syntax errors, bad indentation, and structural mistakes (such as the "did not find expected key" error) with the line that broke. Second, it runs needs / rules / stages validation that matches how GitLab itself validates a config: a job with no script / run / trigger / extends, a job whose stage is not in your stages list, needs and extends references that point at jobs that do not exist, an invalid when value, a rules block that is not a list, legacy only/except, and bad image/services shapes. You get YAML errors and pipeline mistakes in one pass.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I fix the "did not find expected key" error in GitLab CI?',
    a: 'The GitLab CI "did not find expected key" error is a YAML problem, not a pipeline-logic one — it almost always comes from inconsistent indentation, a missing colon, or mixing tabs and spaces, so the parser expected a mapping key and found something else. Paste your .gitlab-ci.yml into this validator: it reports the exact line where the YAML structure broke so you can re-indent or add the missing key and re-validate.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Why does my GitLab CI job fail with a "job has no script" error?',
    a: 'A GitLab job has to do something. A regular job runs commands with script: (or the newer run:), a bridge job starts a downstream pipeline with trigger:, and a job can inherit any of those from another job or hidden template via extends:. A visible job that defines none of them produces the GitLab CI "job without script" error — GitLab rejects it with a message like "job config should implement a script: or a trigger: keyword". This validator flags any visible job missing all four. Hidden templates (keys starting with a dot) are allowed to be partial fragments, so they are not required to have a script.',
  },
];

// ── JSON-LD: SoftwareApplication + FAQPage (shared builders) ─────────────────
const softwareApp = softwareAppLd({
  name: 'GitLab CI Validator',
  description:
    'Free GitLab CI validator that lints your .gitlab-ci.yml for YAML errors and pipeline mistakes in your browser. No install, no project, no login required.',
  url: pageUrl,
  subCategory: 'CI/CD',
  featureList: [
    'Validates .gitlab-ci.yml YAML syntax and reports the exact line and reason on errors',
    'Catches pipeline misconfigurations: undefined stages, jobs without script or trigger, broken needs/rules/extends',
    'Runs 100% in your browser — no install, no GitLab project, and no login or signup',
    'Paste any .gitlab-ci.yml and get instant pass/fail feedback with actionable messages',
    'Your config never leaves the browser — nothing is uploaded to a server',
  ],
  keywords: tool?.keywords.join(', '),
});

const faqPage = faqPageLd(faqs);

// ── HOW IT WORKS pipeline ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const pipeline = [
  {
    title: 'Parse the YAML.',
    body: 'Your .gitlab-ci.yml is parsed with a YAML reader — syntax errors, bad indentation, and structural problems (like GitLab CI’s "did not find expected key" error) are reported with the line that broke.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Split the config.',
    body: 'The top level is split into global keywords (stages, default, variables…), visible jobs, and hidden .templates, so the analyser knows what is a job and what is configuration.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Resolve the stages.',
    body: 'The declared stages: list (or the five defaults: .pre, build, test, deploy, .post) becomes the set every job stage is checked against.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Check every job.',
    body: 'This is the needs / rules / stages validation pass: each job is checked for an executable surface, a known stage, real needs / extends / dependencies targets, a valid when, a list-shaped rules, and sane image / services shapes.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Rank by severity.',
    body: 'Findings are graded error, warning, or info — the pipeline-breaking mistakes rise to the top, ahead of advisory notes like legacy only/except, each with a concrete fix.',
  },
];

// ── PIPELINE CHECKS — each with a broken pattern + the fix ────────────────────
const checks = [
  {
    id: 'undefined-stage',
    name: 'Stage not declared in stages:',
    severity: 'High',
    blurb:
      'A job whose stage: is not in your stages: list (or one of the defaults .pre, build, test, deploy, .post) is a configuration error — GitLab does not know when to run it and refuses the pipeline.',
    badLabel: '.gitlab-ci.yml',
    bad: `# BROKEN — "release" is not a declared stage
stages:
  - build
  - test

release-job:
  stage: release       # not in stages:
  script:
    - make release`,
    goodLabel: '.gitlab-ci.yml',
    good: `# FIXED — every stage used is declared
stages:
  - build
  - test
  - release

release-job:
  stage: release
  script:
    - make release`,
  },
  {
    id: 'no-script',
    name: 'GitLab CI job without script error',
    severity: 'High',
    blurb:
      'A visible job must do something: run commands (script:/run:), start a downstream pipeline (trigger:), or inherit those from another job (extends:). A job with none of them triggers the GitLab CI "job without script" error and is rejected.',
    badLabel: 'job',
    bad: `# BROKEN — this job does nothing
build-job:
  stage: build
  # no script, run, trigger, or extends`,
    goodLabel: 'job',
    good: `# FIXED — give the job a script
build-job:
  stage: build
  script:
    - make build`,
  },
  {
    id: 'bad-needs',
    name: 'needs / extends pointing at a missing job',
    severity: 'Medium',
    blurb:
      'Every entry in needs:, dependencies:, or extends: must reference a job or hidden .template that actually exists in the file. A reference to a missing job breaks the pipeline graph.',
    badLabel: '.gitlab-ci.yml',
    bad: `# BROKEN — "compile" and ".base" never exist
test:
  stage: test
  needs:
    - compile          # no such job
  extends: .base       # no such template
  script:
    - make test`,
    goodLabel: '.gitlab-ci.yml',
    good: `# FIXED — references resolve to real definitions
.base:
  image: golang:1.22

compile:
  stage: build
  extends: .base
  script: make

test:
  stage: test
  needs:
    - compile
  extends: .base
  script: make test`,
  },
  {
    id: 'invalid-when',
    name: 'Invalid when: / non-list rules:',
    severity: 'Medium',
    blurb:
      'when: only accepts on_success, on_failure, always, manual, delayed, or never. rules: must be a YAML list of rule objects — a mapping or a typo here changes (or breaks) when a job runs.',
    badLabel: 'job',
    bad: `# BROKEN — bad when value, rules is a mapping
deploy:
  stage: deploy
  when: sometimes      # not allowed
  rules:
    if: '$CI_COMMIT_TAG'   # rules must be a list
  script: ./deploy.sh`,
    goodLabel: 'job',
    good: `# FIXED — valid when, rules as a list
deploy:
  stage: deploy
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_TAG'
      when: manual
  script: ./deploy.sh`,
  },
];

const checkCount = checks.length;
---

<Shell
  title="GitLab CI Validator — Lint .gitlab-ci.yml Online"
  description="Free GitLab CI validator that lints your .gitlab-ci.yml for YAML errors and pipeline mistakes in your browser. No install, no project, no login required."
  canonical="/gitlab-ci-validator"
  jsonLd={[softwareApp, faqPage]}
>
  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       1) HERO — compact, mesh gradient behind (fixed scrim treatment)
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolHero
    slug="gitlab-ci-validator"
    eyebrow="GitLab CI Validator · CI/CD"
    badges={[
      { label: 'Runs in your browser', variant: 'live' },
      { label: 'No signup', variant: 'neutral' },
      { label: 'Structure-focused', variant: 'neutral' },
    ]}
  >
    <Fragment slot="headline">
      A GitLab CI validator that catches mistakes before the runner does.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      This GitLab CI validator lets you paste a <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no"
        >.gitlab-ci.yml</span
      > and get its YAML errors plus the structural misconfigurations GitLab would reject — undefined
      stages, jobs with no script, broken <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">needs</span
      >/<span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">extends</span>. Validate your
      <span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> instantly, right in your browser. No install, no
      project, no login.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolHero>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       2) THE PLAYGROUND
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="playground" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-canvas-soft pb-20 pt-8 sm:pb-24">
    <div class="container-page">
      <h2 class="sr-only">GitLab CI Validator playground</h2>
      <GitlabCiValidatorPlayground />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       3) WHY IT EXISTS — the gap
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="why" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[0.9fr_1.1fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The Gap</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-ink">
            Valid YAML is only half the job.
          </h2>
          <ToolGapVisual />
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            A <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> can parse as
            perfectly good YAML and still be a broken pipeline. The mistakes that actually fail a run
            are <strong class="font-medium text-ink">structural</strong>: a job pointing at a
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">stage</span> you never declared, a job
            with no <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">script</span>, a
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">needs</span> entry naming a job that does
            not exist, or an <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">extends</span> on a
            template you renamed.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            GitLab’s own <a
              class="link-inline"
              href={glDocsLint}
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">pipeline editor and CI Lint</a
            > catch these — but only after you push to a project and sign in. This
            <span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> checker runs the same high-signal structural
            checks <em>before</em> you commit, entirely in your browser, against GitLab’s <a
              class="link-inline"
              href={glDocsKeywords}
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"><span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> keyword reference</a
            >. It is a GitLab CI linter you can run with no install — and it never asks you to create a
            project or log in.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            It checks both — the YAML <em>and</em> the pipeline structure — so you can validate your
            GitLab CI pipeline before push, with nothing to install and nothing uploaded. Paste your
            <span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> and validate online in seconds, the same way you
            would in a hosted GitLab CI lint, but offline and private.
          </p>
          <p class="body-sm text-mute">
            See the full list in <a class="link-inline" href="#reference">the pipeline checks</a>, or try
            the <a class="link-inline" href="#playground">live playground</a> above.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       4) HOW IT WORKS — numbered pipeline
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolPipeline
    id="how-it-works"
    eyebrow="The Pipeline"
    heading="How this gitlab-ci.yml validator works online."
    lead="Five deterministic steps run end-to-end on every validation — a full GitLab CI YAML lint in the browser, no install and no project, every time."
    steps={pipeline}
  />

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       5) PIPELINE CHECKS — each with broken pattern + fix
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="reference" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <p class="eyebrow">Pipeline Checks</p>
        <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-ink">
          What this GitLab CI config validator checks.
        </h2>
        <p class="body-md mx-auto mt-3 max-w-xl text-pretty text-body">
          Beyond YAML validity, this GitLab pipeline validator looks for the misconfigurations that
          fail a pipeline before a single job runs — so you can check your <span translate="no"
            >.gitlab-ci.yml</span
          > for errors online before you push. Each of the {checkCount} checks below shows the broken
          pattern and the fix.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mx-auto mt-10 grid max-w-5xl gap-6">
        {
          checks.map((check) => (
            <article class="card-soft p-6 sm:p-7">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-3">
                <h3 class="display-sm text-balance text-ink">{check.name}</h3>
                <Badge variant={check.severity === 'High' ? 'high' : 'medium'}>
                  {check.severity} severity
                </Badge>
              </div>
              <p class="body-md mt-3 max-w-3xl text-pretty text-body">{check.blurb}</p>
              <div class="mt-5 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-2">
                <div class="min-w-0">
                  <p class="eyebrow !text-error mb-2">Broken</p>
                  <CodeBlock lang="yaml" filename={check.badLabel} code={check.bad} />
                </div>
                <div class="min-w-0">
                  <p class="eyebrow !text-success mb-2">Fixed</p>
                  <CodeBlock lang="yaml" filename={check.goodLabel} code={check.good} />
                </div>
              </div>
            </article>
          ))
        }
      </div>

      <p class="caption mx-auto mt-10 max-w-3xl text-center text-pretty text-mute">
        Stages, rules and job dependencies are all documented in
        <span translate="no">GitLab</span>’s
        <a
          class="link-inline"
          href={glDocsStages}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">stages reference</a
        > and
        <a
          class="link-inline"
          href={glDocsRules}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">rules reference</a
        >. Legacy <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">only</span>/<span
          class="code-mono text-ink"
          translate="no">except</span
        > and <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">image</span>/<span
          class="code-mono text-ink"
          translate="no">services</span
        > shape checks also run today. As a <span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> validator online,
        every one of these runs as a GitLab CI lint online in your browser — a GitLab CI validator online
        with no install and no project required.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       6) NEXT STEP — dark band with CTAs to related tools
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="next" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-inverse text-inverse-fg">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl items-center gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <p class="eyebrow !text-cyan">Next Step</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-inverse-fg">
            Run GitHub Actions too? Validate those workflows.
          </h2>
          <p class="body-md mt-4 text-pretty text-white/70">
            Many teams run pipelines on both platforms. Once your
            <span class="code-mono" translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> is clean, the
            <span translate="no">GitHub Actions Validator</span> finds the YAML errors and security
            holes in your workflows, and the
            <span translate="no">GitHub Actions Expression Tester</span> evaluates
            <span class="code-mono" translate="no">${'{{ … }}'}</span> expressions before you push —
            both entirely in your browser.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-7 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
            <Button href="/github-actions-validator/" variant="secondary"
              >Open the Actions Validator</Button
            >
            <Button href="/github-actions-expression-tester/" variant="secondary"
              >Open the Expression Tester</Button
            >
          </div>
        </div>
        <CodeBlock
          lang="yaml"
          filename=".gitlab-ci.yml"
          code={`stages: [build, test]

build:
  stage: build
  script: make

test:
  stage: test
  needs: [build]   # ✓ resolves
  script: make test`}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       7) FAQ
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <FaqList faqs={faqs} />

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       Cross-links + footer disclaimer
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolCrossLinks slug="gitlab-ci-validator">
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      The <span translate="no">GitLab</span> CI Validator is one tool in
      <span translate="no">{site.name}</span> — a growing canopy of browser-based validators,
      converters and testers that never touch a server.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="links">
      Related tools: the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/github-actions-validator/"><span translate="no">GitHub</span>
        Actions Validator</a
      > and the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/github-actions-expression-tester/"><span translate="no">GitHub</span>
        Actions Expression Tester</a
      >. Browse the full
      <a class="link-inline" href={navLinks[0].href}>tools directory</a>.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="disclaimer">
      Not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by <span translate="no">GitLab B.V.</span>
      <span translate="no">GitLab</span> is a trademark of <span translate="no">GitLab B.V.</span>,
      used here only descriptively to identify the <span translate="no">.gitlab-ci.yml</span> pipeline
      format this tool checks.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolCrossLinks>
</Shell>
